post_text:
Registration Time!!

We are excited to be going back this fall and want to keep our community safe. As a result, registration will be a little different this year.

Registration packets were sent out and need to be returned on the registration dates and times that are assigned to your family.

Only one family member is to return the packet during your assigned registration time.

Please have your checks written ahead of time, one check for lunch and book fees. All other fees must be paid separately.

Thank you for your kindness, caring, and passion to keeping EACS a safe and productive place for our students to learn!

June 3 at 11:13 AM ·

CONSTRUCTION UPDATE:

The Black Hawk Bridge will now be closing at 7:00am on Friday, June 5.

The previous information about WIS HWY 82 being closed from midnight on June 6 is still accurate; however, IA DOT has decided to complete some bridge maintenance work during the highway closure.

We apologize for not providing this information sooner. While we have been communicating with WIS DOT about this closure for over a year, the IA DOT did not communicate this closure with us.

Both the bridge and HWY 82 are still expected to reopen on Monday, June 15 (though at noon, according to IA DOT, as opposed to midnight, as previously announced by WIS DOT).

post_text:
From Dr. Crozier 4/26/2020 8:50am

I want to congratulate the 2020 Seniors, and we are all very proud of them! We have every intention of having a traditional physical and real graduation ceremony as soon as we possibly can have one. This will be as soon as we can determine a plan that is in compliance with the Governor’s orders, whatever they may be at that time – whether it be inside or out. The virtual graduation at 2:00 on May 10th is intended to supplement, not replace a physical graduation which will occur as soon as feasible. This is so all students have an opportunity to be honored, as invariably some may not be here later in the summer, and then they would have nothing. Again, we congratulate our Seniors!

Thank you,
Dale Crozier

Today, Charles Stendel would have been recognized on stage at the State FFA Convention for receiving his Iowa Degree. However, we can let you in on the AWESOME achievement he has earned!

The Iowa FFA Degree is the highest degree the state can bestow upon a member. Requirements to receive the degree include:

- Active FFA membership for at least 2 years
- Earned and productively invested $1500 or worked 375 hours in a SAE
- Completed 25 hours of community service
- Demonstrate leadership and have a satisfactory scholastic record
- Participated in at least 5 FFA activities above the chapter level

His Supervised Agriculture Experience (SAE) is centered around a placement SAE where he worked on Renk Farms with his family.

We are extremely proud of Charles and know he will continue to do great things in the future.

Congratulations!

post_text:
Congratulations Pete on securing your first grant!! We are so proud of you.

The Lansing FFA Chapter received free tractor tires from Titan Tire today for their tractor restoration project because of Peter. Peter is the chairperson of the Tractor Restoration Committee and was enrolled in an Advanced Power Technology class where he got to work on the tractor. Before school meetings were suspended because of everything going on, Peter had researched, found this grant, obtained all the appropriate signatures and information, filled out the application and submitted the grant all on his own.
Today Peter went to the nearest Titan dealer which was in Waukon and picked up the tires.

Great job Peter for taking the initiative and applying it to something you enjoy doing.

We want to give a huge thank you to five amazing high school students who volunteered their time to help us deep clean our home after the fire. They worked their tail feathers off. Vacuuming the ceilings and walls then wiping them down with dry cleaning sponges and then using a special cleaner to wash everything down. I think they were a little surprised at the amount of soot and smoke that came off.
They will never know how much they are appreciated. May God bless them today and always.

Nick B, Jackson P, Allyvia M, Jenessa S and kyle C you make us all proud ❤

post_text:
Ms. Peregrine has been doing her personalized PD to learn how to incorporate Sound Before Symbol techniques with beginning band. Sound Before Symbol is the idea that students should experience playing an instrument and learn many songs by ear before being introduced to music notation. During this journey she has developed YouTube videos for beginning band so they can learn how to practice at home without the book and she has her 5th and 6th grade bands learn melodies by ear before introducing new full band songs! She has also incorporated a new counting technique that was developed with Sound Before Sight in mind. Here is an example of the videos she developed, each video series is called "Practice with Peregrine".

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QeNjs8tSLy0&list=PLODL1cseJtc7RHjaquyo6sjpUwRyMyEEK

Congratulations to the ensemble acting team: Abby Wood, Jennifer Mitchell, and Ethan Schweitzer for receiving an All State non-performing nomination!

What this non-performing thing means - there can only be so many ensembles selected to perform at the festival for the time allowed. Sometimes there can be more nominations than time to let them perform. The team is still considered Outstanding! in their event and one of the best acting teams in the state. They will receive recognition at the festival as well as presented with the All State medal.

At the state contest there were 66 final ensembles and only 12 received All State recognition: 5 were selected to perform (Decorah, and 4 Dubuque teams) with the other 7 selected as non- performing.

Congratulations Kee ensemble team!

We are partnering with Allamakee Economic Development coordinator Val Reinke and other local businesses to help enlighten students about topics such as lending expectations, insurance, renting, auto loans, mortgage loans and more.

Can't wait to see who shows up next...stay tuned!!

post_text: Our graduates continue to do great things!
shared_text:
Minnesota State University, Mankato - Communication Sciences and Disorders
December 10, 2019 at 12:55 PM ·

Ellie Heiderscheit is currently a second-year graduate student completing her internship at Janseville-Waldorf-Pemberton Community Schools! This is a smaller district but Ellie has still gained great experience in speech, language, social skills, AAC, and counseling than she ever thought possible! She has mainly had a caseload of preschool-aged children but a few have been early elementary, high school, and birth-3. Ellie had nothing but great things to say about her supervisor Vickie Hurd. Ellie Stated, "Vickie is so amazing. She guided me through the first week of school by leading each therapy session while still including me. The second week was all me. She hopped in when she thought necessary but gave me the independence I needed to develop my skills and take advantage of the internship at its fullest. She is always willing to answer any and all of my questions and is very attentive to all my ideas. She's truly an MVP!"

Current bids are Clarinet $200, Saxophone $237 & Oboe $100.

post_text: Way to go Casey!
shared_text:
Northeast Iowa Community College
November 27, 2019 at 3:22 PM ·

Saving lives as a Paramedic is everything Casey Welsh wanted in a career. The Future Ready Iowa Last-Dollar Scholarship brings her closer to that goal.

Casey received a $2,500 Last-Dollar Scholarship to cover the gap between federal, state grants and scholarships to pay for her education in the Northeast Iowa Community College Paramedic program.

“Becoming a Paramedic is a way to put others’ needs before my own. I grew up in an EMS (Emergency Medical Services) household. Both of my parents have been EMTs for more than 25 years. It’s a very rewarding job,” Casey said of her career ambitions.

The Last-Dollar Scholarship is making it happen. “This is $2,500 that I don’t have to pay back, and the funding allows me not to be tied down by student loans,” she said.

The Paramedic program is one of dozens of Northeast Iowa Community College programs that qualify for Last-Dollar Scholarship support. www.nicc.edu/scholarships
